  "unmapped_findings": [
    "The paper states that the parabolic rate constant Kp1 at 600°C is 2.4×10^-10 g^2 cm^-4 sec^-1 in the text, while Table II lists 2.4×10^-12 g^2 cm^-4 sec^-1. The text value is used in the oxidation resistance property, but the discrepancy is noted.",
    "Thermogravimetric oxidation weight-gain data (Fig. 2, approximate values from published graph; units assumed mg/cm^2): At 600°C: 0 h (0), 5 h (0.3), 10 h (0.5), 15 h (0.7), 20 h (0.9), 25 h (1.1), 30 h (1.3). At 700°C: 0 h (0), 5 h (1.2), 10 h (1.4), 15 h (1.5), 20 h (1.5), 25 h (1.5), 30 h (1.5). At 800°C: 0 h (0), 5 h (0.2), 10 h (0.3), 15 h (0.4), 20 h (0.5), 25 h (0.6), 30 h (0.7). At 900°C: 0 h (0), 5 h (0.1), 10 h (0.2), 15 h (0.3), 20 h (0.4), 25 h (0.4), 30 h (0.4). Exact units not specified in caption.",
    "Proposed mechanism for nodule formation and internal oxidation at 600°C: Initially, Al2O3 nuclei cover part of the surface while FeO forms at random sites. CO/CO2 is produced from carbide decomposition at the interface and escapes through pores/microcracks, creating fast diffusion paths. Oxygen diffuses inward through FeO nodules, reacts with Al to form internal Al2O3 precipitates, depleting Al that would otherwise reach the interface and maintain a protective scale. This explains the non-simple parabolic kinetics.",
    "At 700°C and above, internal oxidation is suppressed by the formation of a healing Al2O3 or FeAl2O4 layer that blocks outward Fe cation diffusion. At 900°C, the Al flux is high enough to sustain a continuous Al2O3 scale, eliminating nodules entirely.",
    "The role of carbon (as K-phase carbide) on oxidation: At 600°C, carbide is stable and contributes to CO/CO2 evolution, accelerating oxidation. At higher temperatures, carbide decomposition at the interface becomes ineffective due to rapid Al diffusion and healing layer formation. No decarburization layer was observed at any condition.",
    "Hot forging at 1200°C from 7 cm to 2.5 cm thickness, followed by 1100°C/4 h homogenization, produced a ferrite matrix with dispersed (Fe3AlCx) carbide particles (K-phase), as shown in Fig. 1 (scale bar 40 μm; grain size not numerically reported).",
    "XRD lattice parameters: ferrite a=0.287 nm, carbide a=0.378 nm.",
    "Table III provides quantitative EPMA point analysis of oxide layers after 6, 12, 24, 48, 96 h at 600°C: inner layer Fe 70.9-83.4 wt%, Al 9.0-17.65 wt%; middle layer Fe 49.9-57.2 wt%, Al 9.7-16 wt%; outer layer Fe 61-68.4 wt%, Al 0 wt%.",
    "The infrared image furnace used for TGA had a heating/cooling rate of 100°C/min, and dry air flowed at 100 ml/min."
  ]
